      <div>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1) <span style="color:#FF0000;"><u>Gas tax and car registration fee increases</u></span>—when I saw our state politicians contemplating a <a href="http://www.freep.com/story/news/politics/2015/10/21/michigan-roads-repairs-potholes-legislature/74360028/">gas tax and car registration increase</a> to pay for our roads, I had had enough. I get that the roads need to be fixed and that the money needs to come from somewhere, but why push through a tax increase in a vacuum? All it does is punish the MI consumer.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Why not get rid of MI no-fault insurance (which would <span style="color:#008000;"><u>save the average consumers $1,108 a year</u></span> in expenses) at the same time the state passes a massive tax/fee increase? Gutless or incompetent politicians is my answer.</div><div>&nbsp;</div>
      <div>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2)&nbsp; <span style="color:#FF0000;"><u>Lobbyists</u></span> - when I researched why the MI no-fault law hadn’t already been repealed/replaced I became even more upset.</div></div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Who wants to keep MI no-fault insurance?</div><div><br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;-Insurance companies. Higher premiums with the same profit margins = higher profits<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><div>Insurance companies seemed to have lobbied our state representatives pretty hard to keep no-fault. <a href="http://www.michiganautolaw.com/blog/2015/04/17/senate-passes-sb-248-no-fault-reform/">Click here</a> to read about the lobbying efforts and who took money from the insurance lobby.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;&nbsp; -Insurance agents. They make commissions based on a percentage of premiums. Higher premiums = higher commission. FYI, in addition to being a MI licensed attorney, I also have my property and casualty insurance license allowing me to sell auto insurance (which I do not).<br>&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp;-Trial lawyers love MI no fault. Michigan is the only state where car insurance includes unlimited lifetime personal injury protection. For full disclosure, in law school I clerked for two personal injury firms and after graduating worked for one for a brief period of time.&nbsp; Why do you think MI personal injury attorneys love no fault?&nbsp;</div>
      <div>&nbsp;</div><div><em><span style="color:#FF0000;"><strong>F(forget) the System</strong></span></em><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;I’m not a conformist and I’d submit to you that conformists get rolled when they sit on their hands and do nothing. For years the insurance lobby has had their way with our weak and/or gutless politicians and this is my attempt to allow the people to have a voice in how their state is run.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><div><em><strong>&nbsp;Register for the petition and be heard</strong></em><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;When you register for the petition you are sending a signal to our state politicians that you don’t appreciate their mismanagement of the state’s finances that forced them to increase our gas tax and auto registration fees, and&nbsp; that nothing is being done to stop the runaway costs for EVERY Michigander’s auto insurance (and by the way, it’s a state law that we all have auto insurance).<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;Will anything come from this online petition?<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;I sure hope so. I plan on delivering the petition to each and every state representative in hopes that they will listen and can use the petition to stand up to the insurance lobbyists. But inaction is no longer an option for me and I’d submit, it shouldn’t be for you.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>
